#### Quick Build
You can make a death knight quickly by following these suggestions. First, make Strength your highest ability score, followed by Charisma. Second, choose the **BACKGROUND**

#### Optional Rule: Multiclassing
If your group uses the optional rule on multiclassing in the *Player's Handbook*, here's what you need to know if you choose death knight as one of your classes.

***Ability Score Minimum.*** As a multiclass character, you must have at least a Strength and Charisma score of 13 to take a level in this class, or to take a level in another class if you are already a death knight.

***Proficiencies Gained.*** If death knight isn't your initial class, here are the proficiencies you gain when you take your first level as a death knight: light armor, medium armor, simple weapons, martial weapons.

***Spell Slots.*** Add half your levels (rounded up) in the death knight class to the appropriate levels from other class to determine your available spell slots.

\columnbreak
## Class Features
As a death knight, you gain the following class features.

#### Hit Points
___
- **Hit Dice:** 1d10 per death knight level
- **Hit Points at 1st Level:** 10 + your Constitution modifier
- **Hit Points at Higher Levels:** 1d10 (or 6) + your Constitution modifier per death knight level

#### Proficiencies
___
- **Armor:** All armors
- **Weapons:** Simple weapons, martial weapons
- **Tools:** None
___
- **Saving Throws:** Constitution, Charisma
- **Skills:** Choose two from Athletics, Deception, Intimidation, Investigation, Perception, and Stealth

#### Equipment
You start with the following equipment, in addition to the equipment granted by your background:
- *(a)* a martial weapon or *(b)* two shortswords
- *(a)* five javelins or *(b)* any simple weapon
- *(a)* scale mail or *(b)* chain mail
- *(a)* a dungeoneer's pack or *(b)* an explorer's pack
- A trinket from your past life

\pagebreakNum

### Dark Rebirth
*1st-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

Becoming a death knight results in straddling the line between the living and the dead, existing in both worlds and neither.

Every death knight shares a number of physical traits: their eyes glow with a pale blue light that leaks icy mist, their body feels cool to the touch, and their voice gains a deep echo. Mentally, their emotions and memories from before they became a death knight are typically dulled. They also gain an eternal hunger for causing suffering and death, an addiction that if not sated regularly will inevitably result in insanity.

As a death knight, you gain the following traits:
- You have two creature types: humanoid and undead. You can be affected by a game effect if it works on either of your creature types.
- You have advantage on death saving throws.
- You don’t need to eat, drink, or breathe.
- You don’t need to sleep, and magic can’t put you to sleep. You can finish a long rest in 4 hours if you spend those hours in an inactive, motionless state, during which you retain consciousness.
- You no longer age and will not die from old age.
- At your option, you can also pick from or roll on the Death Knight Quirks table to create a quirk for your character.

##### Death Knight Quirks
d6|Quirks
--|--------
1| Your body temperature becomes arctic, causing your breath to fog and the air around you to gain a deep chill.
2| Your presence feels unnatural, causing others to feel uneasy near you and animals such as dogs to become hostile.
3| You gain a taste for food typically consumed by lower undead, such as humanoid flesh, vermin, and insects.
4| Your memory of your previous life is especially dulled. Alternatively, it is almost entirely intact.
5| You become obsessed with one particular food, drink, or hobby that you liked in life but can no longer enjoy.
6| You are a little too comfortable with death and violence and have no problems with desecrating corpses and graveyards.

\columnbreak
### Rune Weapon
*1st-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You know how to inscribe magical runes onto a weapon, transforming it into the source of your power. 

You perform the ritual to do so over the course of 1 hour, which can be done during a short rest. You can only have a single weapon bound to you. Bonding with a new weapon immediately breaks the bond with any previous rune weapon.

You can't be disarmed of your rune weapon unless you are incapacitated. If it is on the same plane of existence as you, you can summon your rune weapon as a bonus action on your turn, causing it to teleport instantly to your hand.

### Runic Magic
*1st-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have learned to draw on the power of your rune weapon to unleash powerful spells.

#### Cantrips
You know two cantrips of your choice from the death knight spell list. You learn additional death knight cantrips of your choice at higher levels, as shown in the Cantrips Known column of the Death Knight table.

#### Spell Slots
The Death Knight table shows how many spell slots you have to cast your spells of 1st level and higher. To cast one of these spells, you must expend a slot of the spell's level or higher. You regain all expended spell slots when you finish a short or long rest.

For example, if you know the 1st-level spell *death grip* and have a 1st-level and a 2nd-level spell slot available, you can cast *death grip* using either slot.

#### Spells Known of 1st Level and Higher
You know two 1st-level spells of your choice from the death knight spell list.

The Spells Known column of the Death Knight table shows when you learn more death knight spells of your choice. Each of these spells must be of a level for which you have spell slots. For instance, when you reach 5th level in this class, you can learn one new spell of 1st or 2nd level.

Additionally, when you gain a level in this class, you can choose one of the death knight spells you know and replace it with another spell from the death knight spell list, which also must be of a level for which you have spell slots.

#### Spellcasting Ability
Charisma is your spellcasting ability for your death knight spells, so you use your Charisma whenever a spell refers to your spellcasting ability. In addition, you use your Charisma modifier when setting the saving throw DC for a death knight spell you cast and when making an attack roll with one.

<div style="text-align: Center">

**Spell save DC** = 8 + your proficiency bonus + <br> your Charisma modifier

**Spell attack modifier** = your proficiency bonus + <br> your Charisma modifier
</div>

#### Spellcasting Focus
You can use your rune weapon as a spellcasting focus for your death knight spells.

<img src='https://www.gmbinder.com/images/0Juz7SO.png' style='position:absolute; top:800px; left:45px; width:350px; z-index:1' />

\pagebreakNum

### Fighting Style
*2nd-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You adopt a particular style of fighting as your specialty. Choose one of the following options. You can't take a Fighting Style option more than once, even if you later get to choose again.

#### Defense
While you are wearing armor, you gain a +1 bonus to AC.

#### Dueling
When you are wielding a melee weapon in one hand and no other weapons, you gain a +2 bonus to damage rolls with that weapon.

#### Great Weapon Fighting
When you roll a 1 or 2 on a damage die for an attack you make with a melee weapon that you are wielding with two hands, you can reroll the die and must use the new roll, even if the new roll is a 1 or a 2. The weapon must have the two-handed or versatile property for you to gain this benefit.

#### Profane Warrior
You learn an additional two cantrips of your choice from the death knight spell list.

#### Two-Weapon Fighting
When you engage in two-weapon fighting, you can add your ability modifier to the damage of the second attack.

> #### Optional Class Features
> See Tasha's Cauldron of Everything, Pg. 41 for additional Fighting Styles. The Interception, Superior Technique, and Unarmed Fighting styles are appropriate choices for this class.

<div style='margin-top:35px;'></div>

### Runes of Power
*2nd-level death knight feature*
<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You inscribe runes onto your rune weapon that are powered by pain and suffering. Whenever you finish a long rest, your rune weapon gains a number of runes of power equal to your proficiency bonus. Your runes remain powered until your next long rest. You must be holding your rune weapon to use any of its runes of power.

You regain 1 rune of power each time you roll a 20 on the d20 roll for an attack with a rune weapon, or deal a killing blow with a rune weapon to a creature of significant threat (GM’s discretion). You can't maintain more powered runes than your proficiency bonus; any excess runes are lost at the end of your next turn. 

As a bonus action, you can expend these runes to regain an expended spell slot. You must expend one rune for each level of the spell slot.

\columnbreak

### Knighthood
*3rd-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px'></div>

You choose a path of knighthood to follow, becoming either a Knight of Blood, Knight of Frost, or Knight of the Unholy. Your choice of knighthood provides features at 3rd level and again at 7th, 10th, 14th, and 18th level.

#### Knighthood Spells
Each knighthood has a list of associated spells. You gain access to these spells at the levels specified in the knighthood description. Once you gain access to an knighthood spell, you always know it and the spell doesn't count against your number of spells known.

If you gain a knighthood spell that doesn't appear on the death knight spell list, the spell is nonetheless a death knight spell for you.

### Ability Score Improvement
*4th-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px'></div>

When you reach 4th level, and again at 8th, 12th, 16th, and 19th level, you can increase one ability score of your choice by 2, or you can increase two ability scores of your choice by 1. As normal, you can't increase an ability score above 20 using this feature.

#### Deathly Versatility (Optional)
Whenever you reach a level in this class that grants the Ability Score Improvement feature, you can do one of the following, representing a change of focus:
- Replace a fighting style you know with another fighting style available to death knights.
- Replace one cantrip you learned from this class' runic magic feature with another cantrip from the death knight spell list.

### Extra Attack
*5th-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You can attack twice, instead of once, whenever you take the Attack action on your turn. Moreover, you can cast one of your cantrips in place of one of those attacks.

### Improved rune weapon
*6th-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

Your attacks with your rune weapon count as magical for the purpose of overcoming resistance and immunity to nonmagical attacks and damage.

You can also inscribe a rune onto a second weapon, turning it into a lesser rune weapon. As long as you are wielding your rune weapon, this lesser rune weapon can generate runes of power, counts as a magical weapon, and you cannot be disarmed of it unless incapacitated. You can summon both weapons to your hands as part of the same bonus action.

\pagebreakNum

### Runeforging
*6th-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px;'></div>

You have learned to inscribe enchantments onto your rune weapon which draw upon your runes of power to fuel their effects.

**[This is still a WIP. You get a passive benefit based on the rune, and you can expend a rune of power to gain an active ability.]**

